Ringgit Posts Weekly Gain to 13-Year High on Rate Speculation

-- B y   A n d r e a   W o n g
-- 
2011-04-22T08:23:55Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-22/ringgit-posts-weekly-gain-to-13-year-high-on-rate-speculation.html
Malaysia ’s ringgit gained to the
strongest level in more than 13 years on speculation policy
makers will raise  interest rates  to cool rising consumer prices.  Accelerating inflation has stoked speculation Bank Negara
Malaysia will add to last year’s three increases in interest
rates when it next meets on May 5. Global funds bought a
combined $1.7 billion more stocks than they sold in India,  South
Korea , Taiwan and Thailand in the past four days.  “Inflation pressure raises the possibility of a rate
increase next month, which supports the ringgit,” said Suresh Kumar Ramanathan, a Kuala Lumpur-based foreign-exchange
strategist at CIMB Investment Bank Bhd. “The currency may
remain rangebound today as liquidity is quite tight as many
markets are closed.”  The ringgit gained 0.6 percent this week to 3.0045 per
dollar as of 4:18 p.m. in  Kuala Lumpur , its biggest five-day
advance since March 25, according to data compiled by Bloomberg.
It touched 3.0034, the highest level since October 1997. The
central bank has kept its overnight rate at 2.75 percent since
July.  Consumer prices rose 3 percent in March from a year earlier,
the most since April 2009, the statistics department said in an
April 20 statement. The Bank of Thailand raised interest rates
on that day, the sixth increase in less than a year.  The yield on Malaysia’s 4.262 percent government bond due
September 2016 rose one basis point this week to 3.58 percent,
according to Bursa Malaysia. The price dropped 0.07, or 70 sen
per 1,000 ringgit face amount, to 103.30.  To contact the reporter on this story:
